                			<p>
                				<span style="font-size:x-large"><b><a>V</a></b></span>isiting national parks and wildlife sanctuaries is important to understand issues related to wildlife conservation and build public support for the cause. However tourism needs to follow strict guidelines to be beneficial to wildlife conservation.
                			</p>
                			<p>
                				Many tourists visit national parks and wildlife sanctuaries in the name of 'eco-tourism', the density of such tourists who visit the protected areas are unprecedented during peak seasons. This poses as an active threat to wildlife. Roads and developmental activities to aid tourism fragment wildlife habitats leading to disturbances and behavioural changes in wildlife. Extensive roads network is built to facilitate tourism which has a indirect effect on wildlife. Building new roads within protected areas aid spread of exotic plant species such as parthenium, lantana and eupatorium.
                			</p>
                			<p>
                				Forest department which is already short-staffed has to divert the much needed field staff to cater to tourism needs from their core protection activities. This is especially detrimental during crucial periods such as summers when threat of forest fires are high. 
                			</p>
                			<p>
                				Unruly behaviour, uncontrolled traffic into protected areas littering of forests, passive harassment of wildlife, driving at high speeds on main roads of protected areas killing wildlife  are some activities that disturb wildlife and its habitat. Tourists who visit wildlife sanctuaries are unabated and fail to maintain the decorum of the forest causing nuisance in the forests.
                			</p>
                			
